---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Acute Liver Failure" description="Simulation case for acute liver failure management.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Acute Liver Failure</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Gastrointestinal</span>
    <h1>Acute Liver Failure</h1>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>⏱ Duration: 55 minutes</span>
      <span>📊 Difficulty: Advanced</span>
      <span>👥 Team Size: 3–5</span>
      <span>🏥 Setting: ICU / Emergency Department</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="tag">GI</span>
      <span class="tag">Toxicology</span>
      <span class="tag">Critical Care</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Case Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A 45-year-old female, Ms. Karen Walsh, presents with a 5-day history of progressive
      jaundice, right upper quadrant pain, and confusion. Her partner discloses she has been
      taking large amounts of over-the-counter acetaminophen for dental pain, estimated at
      10–12 g/day for the past week.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learners must diagnose acetaminophen-induced acute liver failure, administer N-acetylcysteine,
      manage hepatic encephalopathy and coagulopathy, and initiate the liver transplant evaluation
      pathway using King's College Criteria.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Patient Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Name:</strong> Karen Walsh</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> 45 years</li>
      <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Female</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 65 kg</li>
      <li><strong>PMH:</strong> Depression (on SSRI), Chronic alcohol use</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Sertraline 100 mg, OTC acetaminophen (excessive)</li>
      <li><strong>Allergies:</strong> NKDA</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Initial Vital Signs &amp; Labs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>BP:</strong> 104/68 mmHg</li>
      <li><strong>HR:</strong> 108 bpm</li>
      <li><strong>RR:</strong> 20 breaths/min</li>
      <li><strong>Temp:</strong> 37.8°C</li>
      <li><strong>GCS:</strong> 12 (confused)</li>
      <li><strong>INR:</strong> 4.8 | <strong>AST:</strong> 6,420 U/L | <strong>ALT:</strong> 5,890 U/L</li>
      <li><strong>Bilirubin:</strong> 185 µmol/L | <strong>Creatinine:</strong> 198 µmol/L</li>
      <li><strong>pH:</strong> 7.29 | <strong>Lactate:</strong> 5.2 mmol/L</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li>Diagnose acetaminophen-induced acute liver failure using clinical and laboratory criteria</li>
      <li>Administer IV N-acetylcysteine (NAC) using the correct loading and maintenance dosing protocol</li>
      <li>Manage hepatic encephalopathy including lactulose and rifaximin administration</li>
      <li>Apply King's College Criteria to determine transplant listing criteria</li>
      <li>Manage coagulopathy appropriately (FFP for active bleeding only, not INR correction)</li>
      <li>Involve a multidisciplinary team including hepatology, transplant surgery, and critical care</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Scenario Progression</h2>
    <h4>Phase 1 – Diagnosis &amp; Initial Management (0–15 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Acetaminophen toxicity recognized. IV NAC 3-bag protocol initiated. Serum acetaminophen
      level drawn. Hepatic encephalopathy Grade 2 managed.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 2 – Complication Management (15–35 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Encephalopathy worsens to Grade 3. Airway assessment performed. Coagulopathy managed.
      Hepatology and transplant surgery contacted.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 3 – Transplant Evaluation (35–55 min)</h4>
    <p>
      King's College Criteria applied — patient meets criteria for transplant listing.
      Goals of care discussion initiated. Consent process for transplant evaluation explained.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Debriefing Guide</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Was acetaminophen toxicity identified as the etiology promptly?</li>
      <li>Was NAC given correctly (loading dose and maintenance)?</li>
      <li>Was coagulopathy managed without unnecessary FFP infusion?</li>
      <li>Were King's College Criteria correctly applied?</li>
      <li>How was the goals of care and transplant discussion conducted?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <a href={`${base}cases/`} class="btn btn-primary" style="background: var(--color-primary); color: #fff;">← Back to Cases</a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
